voice_to_text: What's your child say in court that saved someone's life? My five year old daughter's neighbor. Carlos was a 19 year old who worked three jobs to support his younger siblings. Every morning, he'd wave to Lily on his way to work, and she'd run to the fence to show him her drawings. Lily called him her best grown up friend. One Saturday morning, police cars surrounded Carlos's house. There had been a break in six blocks away, and someone gave them Carlos's name as a suspect. The elderly victim, Mrs. Patterson, was in intensive care, fighting for her life after being brutally attacked during the robbery. The evidence seemed overwhelming. Carlos match the description. Young Hispanic male, about six feet tall. He'd been doing odd jobs in that neighborhood. Most damning, they found Mrs. Patterson's stolen jewelry in his work truck. Though Carlos swore someone planted it there. Carlos was arrested and charged with aggravated robbery and attempted murder. His family couldn't afford a good lawyer. The prosecution painted him as a dangerous criminal targeting vulnerable elderly victims. He. I was looking at 25 years to life for a crime I was certain he didn't commit. I knew Carlos was innocent. I'd seen him that Saturday morning working in our shared garden. But the timeline was tight. That's when I remembered. Lily had been playing in our backyard that entire morning, chattering non stop to Carlos while he worked. She'd been helping him plant tomatoes and asking him a Million questions called Carlos's lawyer about Lily's potential testimony. He was skeptical. Child witnesses are unreliable. But I insisted we try. We spent hours preparing Lily, explaining she needed to tell the truth about that Saturday morning when Carlos was planting vegetables. The prosecution had presented their case with confidence, DNA evidence, witness descriptions, and stolen jewelry. When the defense called Lily to the stand, the courtroom went silent. As this tiny girl walked up to the witness box, the judge adjusted the microphone down to her level. Lily, the lawyer began gently, do you remember Saturday morning when Carlos was working in your garden? She nodded seriously. We were planting the tomato babies. She said clearly. Carlos was very careful with them because baby plants can die if you're not gentle. What else do you remember? She brightened. Carlos taught me about bugs, and he showed me how his hands were all dirty from the special plant food. And he said he couldn't touch anything clean until we wash them. The lawyer asked, did Carlos wash his hands that morning? Oh, yes, she I said proudly. We washed them together at the garden faucet with the special soap. Carlos said dirty hands make everything dirty, so we scrubbed until they were super clean. But then Lily added something that changed everything. And Carlos was very sad about his work gloves. The lawyer asked her to explain.

This mom is adjusting to her new normal after losing her hands and legs because of all things, a dog lick. Marie Trainer woke up from a 10 day coma to find her limbs had been amputated. She cried the hardest I ever cried in my life. The life changing tragedy had its origins during a vacation in the Caribbean with her husband. Marie says she was using her key card to access her hotel when she accidentally nicked herself on her wrist. It was a tiny little scratch, a silly accident. It hardly hurt. When Marie came home, her dog Taylor greeted her with lots of kisses. But the dog also licked Marie's scratch. Four days later, Marie got very sick and was rushed to the hospital with a severe infection and septic shock. Her arms were turning black all the way up just below her shoulders. It turns out that her dog's saliva carried a bacteria called capnocytophaga. It's quite common in dogs, but what happened to Marie is a very rare occurrence. Her husband Matthew is doing his best to lift her spirits. I love her to death. She's everything to me.

At Thanksgiving dinner, my sister stood up and announced, we voted, and you're not family anymore. Everyone cheered. I laughed softly and said, then I guess you won't need this. I placed a folder on the table. The moment she opened it, she started screaming. Before we carve the Turkey, Natalie said, rising with that rehearsed smile, there's something we need to say. The room went silent. We had a family vote. You're not family anymore! Cheering. Actual cheering. My cousin Laura clapped like she was at a concert. Uncle Ben raised his wine glass. Even my mother laughed and said, well, someone had to say it. My dad just sipped his beer and muttered, it's probably for the best. Wow, I said, pushing back slowly. You rehearse this? Natalie grinned wider. You've been toxic for years. We're done pretending. It's unanimous, my mother added. I looked around. No one spoke up. Good, I said quietly, reaching into my bag. I figured this might happen. I pulled out a thick folder and placed it in the center. The heavy thought of it hitting the table cut through the laughter. Natalie blinked. What is that? I smiled and folded my arms. Why don't you find out? She snatched it and ripped it open, that snide smirk forming. Then she turned the first page and stopped smiling. Her face went pale. Then she screamed. Blood curdling horror movie scream. Her chair crashed behind her as she bolted upright, slamming the folder shut. You monster! She cried. You messed up freak! Joel! Her husband grabbed the folder. His jaw dropped. Is this. I nodded once. It's all real. Every word, every receipt, every screenshot. Dead silence. You were so sure I wouldn't fight back, I said, standing slowly, so sure I'd stay the quiet one. The doormat. The cash cow. Let me tell you what was in that folder. Five years of records. Over $78,000 sent to family members, all documented. $8,000 for Joel's rehab. Actually a spa retreat. $2,300 for Natalie's emergency dental work, elective veneers. $12,000 for mom's credit card debt. $4,500 for a family emergency. Actually a Cabo trip. Screw. Screenshots of Natalie calling me a cash cow with no spine, posts where they mocked me, texts where she called me manipulative for refusing to co sign her business loan. And the cherry on top, hotel receipts showing Natalie spent three nights in Santa Monica with someone named Alyssa, charged to Joel's credit card. That's what made her scream. She wasn't just exposed, she. It was dismantled, fact by fact. Joel flipped through pages, his face paling. What's this about Santa Monica? Who's Alyssa? Why were you at a hotel for three nights on my credit card? Silence. Let's be reasonable. My mom tried. Sure, I said. Let's talk about when you called me a parasite while cashing my check. We were under stress, she stammered. No, I snapped. You were under stress, and I bailed you out every time. The one time I say no, I'm the enemy. My dad spoke up. You're making this bigger than it is. You let them do this for years. I said, you knew. You saw it. You let it happen because it was easier. You're just bitter because no one needs you anymore. Natalie shouted. Wrong. I said coldly, I'm not bitter. I'm done. You think this

Foster children. What's the most insane thing you ever experienced? When I was 10, I got placed with the lanes. They seemed normal at first. Nice house, good food. Even gave me my own bedroom with cartoon wallpaper. But something felt weird from day one. They never let me go outside alone, not even to the mailbox. If I wanted to play in the backyard, one of them had to watch me through the window. When I asked why, they said it was for my safety. I figured all foster parents were protective like that. At school, if I got any papers or notes, I had to hand them over the second I walked in the door. They said they needed to check everything for my own good. They locked up my backpack at night and went through it while I slept. I thought this was normal, too. The weirdest thing was the computer. I had one in the living room, but I wasn't allowed to touch it. Ever. They said the internet was dangerous for kids. When other kids at school talked about games or videos they saw online, I just. Just nodded along and pretended I knew what they meant. One night, I lost a tooth. I put it under my pillow like always, expecting to wake up to a dollar or some quarters. Instead, I found a tiny folded note written in handwriting I'd never seen before. It said, you're not who they think you are. Check Behind the mirror, I scared out of my mind. At school the next day, I asked my teacher, Missus Kim, if the tooth fairy ever left notes instead of money. She laughed and said, no, the tooth fairy only brings coins. That made me even more confused. At night, while the lanes were downstairs watching their usual cop shows, I carefully pulled the mirror off my bedroom wall. My hands were shaking the whole time. Behind it was a small hole cut into the wall, and inside was a plastic bag stuffed with papers. I pulled everything out. Birth certificates, newspaper clippings, photos of kids who looked like me but weren't me. One photo showed a little girl with my exact eyes but different hair. Another showed a teenager who could have been my sister. Then I found the missing child flyer. It had a picture of a six year old girl named Sophie Blanchard, missing for four years. The girl in the photo looked exactly like me, just younger. My stomach dropped to the floor. There were handwritten notes, too. They rename all the kids. Tell someone the truth. Call Aunt Jane. She's still looking. I spent the next week acting totally normal, eating dinner and doing homework like nothing happened. But inside, I was freaking out. During lunch at school, I snuck into the classroom and use the phone to call the number written on one of the papers. A woman answered, and when I said the name Sophie Blanchard. She started crying so hard I could barely understand her. She kept asking where I was, if I was safe, if I remembered her. I hung up because I got scared. That weekend, two people from child services showed up at our door without warning. The lanes tried to act calm, saying it must be some kind of mistake. But the officers found more hidden files in the attic.

How did the worst misunderstanding of your life lead to meeting your spouse? The building manager knocked on my door at 6 a m. Sir, open up or we'll call the police. My neighbour hid behind him, carefully holding a binder labelled evidence. The manager cleared his throat. Sir, we need to discuss some serious allegations. We've received complaints of your stalking behaviour. Would you mind letting us in? I was surprised. Stalking? No, I'm sure this is all just a funny misunderstanding, I said. Thank. What could I have even done that felt like stalking? Then let us in, he insisted coldly. They walked in and immediately started looking around. My neighbor pointed at my balcony. That's where he watches me every morning. Look, there's even a notebook. She grabbed it before I could react and started reading out loud. 5:00am, she left, crying. 602:00am, she came back. 7:00am, she looked tired, didn't eat breakfast. Her hands started shaking in fear. The manager frowned. You're documenting her routine? I shook my head. No. Well, yes, but it's because this goes back three months. Every single day? She asked, covering her mouth. My neighbor spotted my phone on the counter. Stay right where you are. Passcode now, he said, radioing security in case things went south. 2,352, I told. They opened up my gallery and scrolled through the dozens of pictures from the park. She was in every single one. Oh my god, she said, showing the manager. He's been Photographing me everywhere I go. The manager's expression darkened. Okay, I know this looks bad, but please let me explain. I begged, but my neighbor refused, pulling out more evidence. Text messages from her friends. Look, he followed me to the pet store last week. My friend saw him hiding behind the dog food aisle. The manager studied the photos. He always asked me weird questions, too. He's like, are you going anywhere overnight this weekend? And stuff. Like, why would you need to know that? My neighbor was almost crying, and he somehow knew my mom was sick. I never told him that, either. The manager noticed a she's bag by the door. What's in there? Wait. He opened it. Out came five different types of cat food with heating pads and antibiotics. They stared at it completely confused. I side, I've been trying to tell you guys I'm not stalking. Look. I grabbed my phone and opened up the gallery again, zooming into the pictures. Each one had pictures of the stray cats my neighbor started taking care of a few months ago. The manager and my neighbor exchanged looks like I just made up the worst excuse ever. Right, cats, the manager said sarcastically. You expect us to believe you've been stalking her for cats? My neighbor shook her head. That's sick. Using innocent animals as your cover story. No, I just. Look, I said, frustrated, grabbing my note.

What's the most shocking thing you've accidentally discovered? I finally successfully snuck my crush over one night without my parents noticing. But as he had to go home, we were almost in the clear. We snuck downstairs. But as soon as we opened the front door, the lights flicked on. I felt my heart stop and saw my dad standing there in his boxers. What the hell is this? He was holding my iPad, scrolling through our texts from earlier where he asked if he could come over after my parents went to bed. My dad charged at him and this poor guy scrambled out the front door while my dad shouting about get out and never come back. Dad's face is purple as he announces, I'm installing cameras, every room, every angle. You wanna act like you can't be trusted? Fine. Now you can't be. Mom stumbles downstairs asking what's happening, but Dad's already on his phone ordering equipment from some security website. I thought he was joking, but by noon, they were literally everywhere, living room, kitchen, hallway, even one pointed at my bedroom door. 47 cameras total, I counted. He sets up this whole command center on his laptop in his room, multiple screens showing every angle of our house like he's running a casino. This is for your safety. There won't be any teen pregnancy in my house. Day three and I can't breathe without dad texting me. I'm doing homework and who was at the Door, it's the mailman. He rushed home one day because he heard me talking on the phone while my friend Reese was coming over to study. He burst into my room thinking Reese was a boy literally holding a baseball bat. However, I started noting weird things going on. I decided to check his camera system myself one day and noticed activity. At 3:00am, Dad emerges from his room fully dressed, jeans, boots, like he's ready to go on a date. Mom's already completely passed out from her long day and doesn't even notice him leaving. He checks the cameras to make sure I'm in bed, not knowing I'm watching him check on me. Then he just leaves. Nothing happens until he comes back at 4:00am, hair messy, sneaks back into bed with mom before she noticed he was even gone. I didn't believe what I was seeing. I had to make sure this was real. But the very next night, one night, the camera catches him coming back with lipstick on his collar that he frantically scrubs off in the downstairs bathroom. I started crying while watching this. My, my own dad even going as far as to say, if I catch that kid around here again, I'll kill him. My mom just laughs. I can't stand watching her live this lie anymore. Saturday night, after dad sneaks out again, I wake mom. There's something you need to see. I show her all the footage, him leaving at 2:00am Coming back to shoveled the lipstick, everything. Mom's face goes from confusion to rage. Oh, my god. After 20 years.

The Blackhawk was 15 seconds away from crossing paths with the jet. He told her he believed that air traffic control wanted them to turn left towards East River Bank. If they would have turned left, it would have opened up more space between the helicopter and this American Airlines flight. She didn't turn left though. Now, as you guys know, it took quite a while before they would release Rebecca Lobo's name, 3 days to be exact. And sources are claiming it's because they wanted to scrub her social media. voice_to_text: Never seen such a ridiculous giant. He rolled straw into a cigarette on a whim. Then to light it, he tore off someone's roof and used a fireplace as a lighter. But that's not all. After lighting the cigarette, he sat on a granary, slowly enjoying it. The villagers were terrified. To calm the people, the king posted a notice to hunt him down. Days passed. No one volunteered. Just when the king was out of ideas, a little Taylor killed seven flies in one smack. Feeling proud, he wanted to show off. Words spread fast. The guards heard about it and immediately told the king. The king summoned the Taylor, asking if he really killed seven. The Taylor thought he meant flies and confidently said yes, even exaggerated a bit. The king was impressed. He gave the tailor the mission defeat the giant. The tailor was stunned. Before he could protest, the king added, complete this and the princess is yours. Before he knew it, the princess ran over and kissed him. Wildly, the tailor accepted the task. The villagers cheered as he left the city gates. When the gates closed, he snapped back to reality. Scared, he tried to go back. Seeing the hopeful faces of the people and Princess, he couldn't refuse. With a racing heart, he set off. A little tailor versus a giant. He had no idea what to do. The ground shook. A massive shadow loomed. He looked up, almost crushed by the Giant's 45 foot, foot. Panicking, he ran through the forest. He reached a lake, thought it would slow the giant. But to him, it was just a puddle. No use at all. Finally, the Taylor hid inside a pumpkin. The giant, tired, sat on a nearby house to rest. He spotted the Taylor and was stunned. Worse, he grabbed the pumpkin and the Taylor was inside. Naturally, he got tossed into the giant's mouth. Luckily, while the pumpkin rolled, the Taylor grabbed the giant's pendulum hammer. The giant thought he choked, drank a ton of water, and the tailor was swept into the stomach. Luckily, he grabbed a bell rope and pulled himself out as the giant yanked. But now the giant spotted him. With nowhere to run, the tailor pulled out Scissors. The angry giant slapped down. But the Taylor hid in his sleeve. The giant reached in. Exactly what the Taylor planned. He sewed the giant's hand through the slit. Done, he climbed onto the giant's head, threw a rope around its nose. The giant couldn't resist. The tailor wrapped the rope down all the way to its feet. A strong pull and the giant tumbled to the ground. With the giant subdued, the Kingdom built an amusement park powered by the giant's own breath.

voice_to_text: I told my wife her family problems weren't my problems, and it made her lose her mind. I was sitting on the edge of our bed, crying my absolute eyes out because I just got a call telling me that my mother had passed away in her sleep. My wife, Sonic, walked through the door, saw me crying, and instead of comforting me, she said, the kitchen sink is clogged again. I looked up at her, trying to process what I just heard. Sonic, I just found out my mom died. She stood there in the doorway, arms crossed, and I'll never forget what came out of her mouth next. Okay, but that's not my problem. My problem right now is the kitchen sink, and I want it fixed. The words hung in the air between us like poison. 23 years, a whole life built together. And she was standing there telling me my mother's death wasn't her problem because the damn sink was clogged. I sat there staring at her, waiting for her to realize what she just said. Maybe take it back. Show some sign she was human. Are you serious right now? I asked, my voice barely a whisper and still rough from all the crying. Do you even love me? She actually rolled her eyes. Grow up, Dave. Your family problems aren't my problems. The sink needs to be fixed, and I have friends coming over in an hour. My family problems aren't her problems. That's What she had to say in response to my mom dying. I stood up, walked past her to the kitchen, and fixed the sink. It took me 10 minutes. Then I sat alone in our bedroom to plan my mother's funeral. And realized the woman I'd married was a stranger. That night, I made a decision. If that's how she wanted our marriage to work, that's exactly what she'd get. Three weeks after Mom's funeral, I was in the garage working on my car when Sonic burst through the door. She was on the phone with her brother, yelling about some emergency. Hold on, I'm getting the money right now. She hung up and marched over to me. My brother needs $2,000 by tomorrow or he's getting evicted. I need you to transfer it from our savings right now while I'm watching, so I know it's done. She stood there with her phone out, waiting. I just kept working on the engine. Dave, I'm not playing around. Transfer the money! I straightened up, slowly, grabbed a rag, and while wiping the grease off my hands, I looked her in the eye and said, your family problems aren't my problems. She paused, processed what I just said, and then started screaming. Are you seriously being this petty? My brother is about to be homeless, and you're, what, trying to make some point? She shoved her phone in my face. Just do it now! I pushed her phone away gently. No, I Won't your brother your problem? Her face went from annoyed to furious in seconds. This is our money. I work, too. Transfer it right now or I swear to God, Dave. Or what? You'll ignore me like you did when my mother died? Oh, wait, that already happened. voice_to_text: I refused to share a room with a one year old, twin, two year olds and a four year old. I was 18 when my Aunt Carla invited me and my friend Beth to her ranch house for 4th of July. Now this place was huge. Four bedrooms with queen beds, a master bedroom and this massive kids room with about 6 beds and a loft. I was pumped to finally get away from the city and run around on their land with Beth. We got there, I found out the sleeping situation. Me and Beth were supposed to bunk with four screaming kids while their parents got their own room. My cousin Ryan, who's 16 also got his own space with our other relatives. But I us, nope. We got babysitting duty. The kids belong to my Aunt Julie and Uncle Mark. These people had four kids under 5 and none of them slept through the night. I knew this because I'd stayed at their house once before and it was pure hell. The baby would cry, wake up the twins who would then wake up the four year old and it was just chaos all night long. I told Aunt Carla we'd rather sleep on the couch. That's when things got ugly. Aunt Julie completely lost it. She started screaming about how we got to bring a friend so we should watch her kids. She said someone needed to be responsible for them during the night. And since Ryan was a growing boy who doesn't know how to take care of kids. It had to be us. The way she said it, like we were hired help or something, made my blood boil. Nobody else wanted to get involved. Aunt Carla just shrugged and said we needed to figure it out ourselves. So I ignored Julie and started setting up blankets on the couch with Beth. That's when Julie really snapped. He marched over and threw all our stuff off the couches onto the floor. She got right in my face and said we had to sleep with her kids or we couldn't stay at all. Beth was standing there looking mortified because this crazy woman was screaming at us over sleeping arrangements. I told Julie we were leaving if we couldn't sleep on the couch. She, I started screaming even louder about how I drove up with my dad's boat and if I left, nobody could pull it around the property, like that was somehow my problem. The whole family just stood there watching this woman have a complete meltdown over us not wanting to be unpaid babysitters. My cousin Ryan was smirking like this was entertainment. Aunt Carla kept saying, just work it out instead of telling her sister to calm down. I'd had enough. I went outside and started loading our stuff back into my truck. Julie followed me out there, still yelling about how I was being selfish and that she needed a break. From her kids. She actually said I should be grateful for the chance to help family. Beth was standing by the truck looking like she wanted to disappear. This wasn't exactly the fun weekend getaway I'd promised her. I could see other relatives peeking out the windows watching the drama unfold. I hitched the boat trailer back up while Julie kept ranting. I was going on about how young people today don't respect their elders and how I was setting a bad example. Then she tried a different approach and started crying about how overwhelmed she was with four kids and how she just needed one night of good sleep. I almost felt bad for a second until I remembered she'd thrown our stuff on the floor and screamed at my friend. I told her that.

I wasn't friendly with my partner's daughters. Now that they've warmed up to me. So I'm 42, dating Tim, who's 59. Guys, broke as hell. But I've got money from a trust fund. His daughters thought I was some gold digger trying to steal their dad's cash. Plot twist, dude literally has no money. Tim's wife died of cancer like three times she got it. This man emptied everything. Credit cards maxed out, second mortgage, retirement, gone. Everything just to keep her alive long enough to see both daughters get married. The house was underwater on payments and he was looking at bankruptcy when he moved in with me. His daughter Butters live six hours away. We drove there for Christmas two years in a row and these girls treated me like absolute garbage. They pulled him away whenever he tried to include me in conversations. Her husbands couldn't even say hi to me because the daughters would literally talk over me every time they tried. First year, Tim told them off and they gave this fake apology, said seeing dad with someone who wasn't mom was too painful. Fine, whatever. Second year, they did the exact same thing. I was done. This year, I told him he could go see his daughters, but I wasn't dealing with that crap again. He wasn't thrilled because I usually help with the driving when his back starts acting up. His 2,010 piece of junk car was falling apart anyway, so I leased Him a nice luxury car through my brother's dealership. Tim calls the girls all excited about the new car, thinking he can visit more often without his back killing him. Big mistake. They absolutely lost it. Started screaming about how he was spending their dead mother's money on some house and fancy car to impress his bimbo bartender girlfriend. Said he never offered them money for their weddings. That's when everything came out. These girls had no clue about the debt. They thought there was some massive life insurance payout sitting around. They didn't know about the maxed credit cards or that the house was about to get foreclosed on. They had no idea Tim was basically homeless until he moved into my place. I also didn't realize it was my house he was living in. Dude pays the water Bill because he takes forever showers and splits groceries. That's it. Now suddenly these girls want my phone number. They're sorry I felt lonely at Christmas. How sweet. They want to visit us next summer, too. Funny how that works out since I live near the beach.

My dad suddenly burst into my room and yelled, did you eat the pills from my drawer? Yeah, I said, looking up from my phone where I've been scrolling TikTok for the past hour. Dad's face went from worried to absolutely terrified in half a second. Like I just told him I jumped off a roof. How many? How many did you take? His voice cracked and he grabbed my shoulders hard enough to hurt. Two. I had a headache from studying. He actually stumbled backward and had to grab my desk to keep from falling. Oh, god, no, no, no! He was pacing now, running his hands through his hair so violently, I thought he'd rip it out. When. When did you take them? Like an hour ago. Dad, what's wrong? You're scaring me. He stopped dead and his face went even wider. I took one, too, 20 minutes ago. I thought they were Tylenol. He sat on my bed and put his head in his hands, and that's when my stomach dropped. Because dad never panics. Not even when our house almost burned down last year. We need to tell your mother. Oh, god, she's going to kill me. He looked at me with genuine fear in his eyes. You feel anything? Dizzy? Hot? Is your heart racing? I wasn't before, but now my heart was pounding from pure terror. Mom came running when dad yelled for her, and I've never seen someone's expression change so fast. Confused. To furious to absolutely horrified in about two seconds. You left them where she could find them? She was screaming now, actually screaming. Are you insane? She rushed over, checking my pulse with shaking hands, looking at my pupils, feeling my forehead. Baby, how do you feel? Any nausea, chest pain, trouble breathing? Before I could answer, my older brother Matt walked in, looking annoyed until he saw mom basically giving me a medical exam while dad sat there looking like he might puke. What's happening? Matt asked, but mom was already on the phone with someone nearly crying. Yes, my 15 year old daughter. She took two of them about an hour ago. No, my husband took one, too. Dad kept checking his own pulse and muttering about contraindications and drug interactions.

You ever had your meth dealer become your landlord? I've been clean for six months. When I saw Domingo's name on the lease agreement, my stomach dropped. The property management company secretary smiled at me. Mister Vega is one of our best landlords. Never had a complaint. I stared at the signature line, hand trembling. Of all the apartment complexes in Tucson, I picked the one owned by my former dealer. Is there a problem? She asked. I forced myself to sign. I needed this place. My recovery housing was kicking me out, and everywhere else required credit checks. I'd fail moving day. I kept my head down, praying I wouldn't see him. But there he was, fixing a broken gate in the courtyard. Domingo looked different. Clean cut, polo shirt, tool belt. Nothing like the strung out dealer who used to run three trap houses. He glanced up and recognition flashed across his face. Alejandro, he said quietly. Not my real name, but the one I'd used buying from him. It's Paul now, I said. Paul Morrison. He nodded slowly. I go by Domingo Vega these days. Not Dom, not D money. Just Domingo. We stood there awkwardly until he spoke. Apartment 2:37, right. Air conditioner works, but the disposal's touchy. Don't put pasta down it. Normal landlord talk. Except we both knew the last time we'd seen each other. I've been begging for a front, promising I was good for it. He laughed and told me to come. Back with ash or collateral. That was the night I overdosed in a Walgreens bathroom. Waking up in the hospital was my rock bottom. For three weeks, we avoided each other. Then my kitchen flooded. I had no choice but to call maintenance. Domingo showed up himself with tools and a shop vacuum. As he worked, he said, I got clean four years ago. Lost my connect, got arrested and went through withdrawal in county. Best thing that ever happened to me. I watched him expertly fixing my pipes. You? He asked. Six months. I said, seven. Tomorrow. Actually, he smiled. The first year is hell. Second year is harder. Third year, you stop counting days. How'd you go from dealing to this? I asked. Flamingo dried his hands on a rag. My grandmother left me money, but it was in a trust. Couldn't touch it while I was using. Got clean, got the money, bought this place. As a reminder, he gestured around. Half these tenants are in recovery. I don't advertise it, but word gets around. I look at him differently. You're running sober housing? Nah, he said. Just a landlord who gets it. No judgment, but no enabling either. A month later, I relapsed. Not meth, but alcohol, which for me always LED back to meth. Domingo found me passed out in the laundry room at 3:00am. Bottle of vodka smashed on the floor. I expected fiction. Instead, he helped me to my apartment and sat with Me. While I cried. I'm gonna lose everything again. I sobbed. Maybe, he said. Or maybe this is just a stumble. Your choice. He left his number. Call me instead of your dealer. I'll tell you all the reasons it's not worth it. I did call him. Two nights later, when the cravings hit hard. He talked me through it, sharing his own stories of almost relapsing. You know what saved me, he said. Remembering the faces of people I sold to. Kids like you wasting away, begging for another hit. I carry that guilt every day. His voice cracked. I can't undo what I did, but I can make sure my buildings are safe places for people trying to get better. Three months passed. I stayed clean. Got a job at a warehouse, started therapy. One evening, flamingo knock on my door. Need to ask you something. Said. He explained that another tenant, a young woman named Carla, was struggling, fresh out of rehab, no support system. Would you consider being her recovery buddy? Just someone to check in with? I wanted to say no, that I was barely keeping myself together, but I remembered him sitting with me that night. Yeah, I said. I can do that. Carla and I became friends. We went to meetings together, cooked meals, watch movies. Having someone else to focus on helped me stay accountable. When she celebrated six months clean, the domino threw a small party in the courtyard. Nothing fancy. Just cake and coffee. But five other tenants showed up. Turns out we were all in recovery. All placed here by Domingo's quiet network of helping without advertising it. One day, while paying rent, I finally asked him directly. Do you ever regret what you did before? Domingo looked out his office window at the courtyard where Carla was teaching another tenant to garden. Every day, I sold to maybe 300 people over two years. Eleven of them died. I know their names. He pulled out a worn notebook. Pages filled with names and dates. I keep track of everyone I hurt and everyone living here who's getting better. That's my apology to them. Last week marked my 2 years clean. Domingo reduced my rent without me asking. Said it was a long term tenant discount. We both knew what it really was. Recognition that I made it through the hardest part. Yesterday, a new tenant moved in, shaky and thin, clearly fresh from detox. Domingo introduced us. Paul here knows the neighborhood. He can show you around. The kid looked scared but grateful. After Domingo left, he asked me, is the landlord cool? Someone said he used to be in the game. I thought about how to answer. He was. Now he's something else. Someone who understands exactly what you're going through and won't judge you for it. The kid nodded, looking relieved. As I helped him carry boxes up the stairs, I realized Domingo had

I changed my name because my parents named me Corstal Crystal. My parents actually looked at a Newborn baby and thought, let's spell crystal like we're trying to unlock a cheat code. For 18 years I dealt with this disaster of a name that looked like someone sneezed while typing. Every first day of school was the same. I'm nightmare. Teachers would get to my name on the roll call and just stop. Dead silence. Then they'd attempt some butchered pronunciation like kirstyle or questilly. I'd have to raise my hand and say, it's just crystal, but spelled like my parents hate me. The worst part wasn't even the pronunciation, it was the assumptions. People would see my name written down and immediately think I was some exotic foreign exchange student or that my family was super religious. I got asked if I was Muslim at least once a week. Random people would come up to me asking what country I was from or what language my name came from. I'd have to explain that. No, my parents just thought they were being creative when they were really just being cruel. My mom was the worst about it. She'd email every single teacher at the beginning of each school year with the whole paragraph about how to pronounce my name correctly and the cultural significance behind the spelling. There was no cultural significance. She just saw the name Crystal in a baby book and decided to make it look fancy. When I was 15, I started telling people to just save my name as Crystal in their phones. It made everything easier. But my mom found out when she saw a text from my friend Jess that just said Crystal, and she completely lost it. She grounded me for two weeks and made me write apology letters to all my friends explaining the proper way to spell my name. That's when I knew I was changing it. The second I turned 18, the day after my birthday, I marched down to the courthouse with all my paperwork. The clerk was super nice about it. She

How did you scam the scammer? Last Tuesday, I was making lunch for my kids when my phone rang. Unknown number, but I picked up anyway. Big mistake, right? This guy with a thick accent starts telling me he's from the IRS and I owe $4,200 in back taxes. Says if I don't pay immediately with gift cards, the police will arrest me within an hour. Now, here's the thing. I literally just got my tax refund two weeks ago. My accountant, Beth, handled everything perfectly and I even got money back. So I knew this dude was full of it. But instead of hanging up, something clicked in my brain. My neighbour, Missus Kim, had fallen for this exact scam last month and lost $800. Time for payback. I started crying into the phone. Oh, no, I can't go to jail. My kids need me. The scammer ate it up. He told me to go to target and buy iTunes gift cards worth $2,000 as a first payment. I said I needed an hour to get the money together. First I called my cousin Jake, who's a cop, told him what was happening, and he said to keep the guy on the line as long as possible. Then I started my revenge tour. I called the scammer back an hour later, sobbing. I'm at target, but I'm so confused. Which gift cards do I buy? He walked me through it step by step. I pretended to be this helpless Single mom who didn't understand technology. Sorry, can you repeat that? My hands are shaking so bad. For the next 20 minutes I wandered around target asking him questions. Do I need the physical cards or the digital ones? The cashier is asking for I D. Is that normal? Sorry, my 4 year old is having a meltdown in the cart. Finally I told him I had the cards. He was so excited. Probably thinking about his commission. I read him the first number. Okay, it starts with 5. Wait, is that a 5 or an S? The scratching messed it up. I gave him completely fake numbers, mixing up digits, going super slow. After 20 minutes of this, he got frustrated. Ma'am, those numbers don't work. Go buy new cards. So I did the whole routine again. Drove to Walmart, called him back crying harder. The first store's cards didn't work. Are you sure you're really from the IRS? This time I really went for it. I'm in the Walmart parking lot fake crying so loud. Other shoppers were staring. My kids are asking why mommy is buying $5,000 worth of iTunes cards. My daughter wants to know if we're going to be homeless. The scammer actually tried to comfort me. Don't worry, ma'am, just read me the numbers and everything will be fine. I fed him another set of fake numbers, this time adding sorry, my baby spilled juice on the card. Let me clean it off. Three Hours in, this guy had wasted his entire afternoon on me. I could hear other scammers in the background getting impatient. Supervisor was probably wondering why he hadn't closed the deal yet. That's when I went for the kill shot. You know what's funny? I just got off the phone with my cousin Jake. He's the police officer standing right next to me. And he says you're not from the IRS at all. Dead silence. Then what? Yeah, Jake says the IRS doesn't take gift card payments and he's got all your phone records now. Something about tracing the call. He wants to know if you'd like to chat with him directly. The line went dead so fast I thought my phone broke. But here's where it gets good. I posted the whole story on Facebook with screenshots of the call log. My neighbour started sharing it, then my kids school shared it. Then somehow the local news picked it up. They interviewed me about scammer tactics and how to protect yourself. Three weeks later, our neighbourhood association voted me Community Hero of the month for wasting a scammer's time and protecting other families. They gave me a fifty dollar gift card to the grocery store, which was way better than losing thousands to some creep.

Schizophrenics. What's the scariest hallucination you've ever had? When I was 17, I started hearing whispers, just little ones at first, like when you're falling asleep and think someone called your name. My mom said it was stress from school and I believed her because the voices only came when I was freaking out about tests or whatever. But by the time I turned 19, the whispers got clearer. They weren't random anymore. They told me things that were going to happen. The first real prediction was about my coworker Jake spilling coffee on his white shirt at exactly 9:47 in the morning. I thought I was losing it, but I kept checking the clock anyway. At 9:47 on the dot, Jake knocked over his mug all over himself. My hands started shaking. How could my brain know that? The voice came back two days later. This time it said there would be a three car crash at the intersection near my apartment. Don't walk that way. After work, I took a different route home and sure enough, the evening news showed twisted metal and ambulances at that exact spot. I started calling them the forecasters. They felt like guardian angels or something keeping me safe. The predictions kept coming and they were always right. My girlfriend would text me five minutes after they told me she would, my bus would be late by exactly 12 minutes, like they said. I stopped questioning it, started trusting these voices like they Were gods. But then the predictions got darker. They told me not to visit my brother's graduation party because someone would get hurt. I stayed home and found out later that two guys got in a fight and one ended up in the hospital with a broken nose. They warned me that my girlfriend was cheating. I didn't want to believe it, but I checked her phone and found the messages. Everything they said was true. The forecasters had never been wrong, not once. So when the voice told me I was going to get shot that Tuesday, I completely lost it. They said the bullet was coming and there was nothing I could do to stop it, just prepare. I called in sick to work, locked every door and window in my apartment. I even moved my dresser in front of the front door. I sat in my bathroom with a knife listening for footsteps in the hallway. The voice kept repeating, the bullet is coming, the bullet is coming. I stayed awake for 23 hours straight, jumping at every sound.

Did you realise you raised your daughter right? My daughter Elia destroyed our neighbour's face with a baseball bat. I was in the middle of a work meeting when my phone lit up with a call from my neighbour Roman. His voice was shaking with fury. Your daughter Elia is psychotic. She attacked me with a baseball bat. I was just checking on her like you asked and she broke my effing nose! The cops are already here. My blood ran cold. Elia was a straight A student and had never been in a fight in her life. I ran to my car and started driving. The 20 minute drive home felt like hours, my mind racing through every possible scenario. Roman's words kept echoing in my head. Psychotic act. Broke my nose. What could have possibly happened? By the time I reached our driveway, my shirt was soaked with sweat. The scene that greeted me was even worse than I'd imagined. Two police cruisers were parked outside with their lights flashing and half the neighborhood had gathered on their lawns to stare. Roman was on our front porch and was holding a towel to what was clearly a broken nose. His white polo shirt was stained red and he was gesturing wildly at two officers who were taking notes. She. He needs to be locked up! He was shouting. This is assault with a deadly weapon! I want charges pressed! Elia sat on our front lawn with her knees Pulled to her chest, staring at the grass. She looked so small, so defeated. The female officer approached me as I got out of the car. Sir, your neighbor claims your daughter attacked him unprovoked with a baseball bat. If he presses charges, we're looking at aggravated assault. That could mean juvenile detention. My stomach dropped. Roman saw me and immediately started ranting. She's violent, unhinged. I was just checking on her like you asked, making sure she got home safe from school, and she came at me like a wild animal. Look at my face. My nose is broken. I might need surgery. The male officer showed me photos they'd taken of Roman's injuries. His nose was def. Broken, already starting to bruise. Your daughter hasn't said a word since we arrived, the officer said quietly. We need to know what happened here. I walked past Roman, ignoring his continued shouting about pressing charges and teaching violent children a lesson. Then I knelt down beside Elia on the grass, and I put my hand on her shoulder. She flinched, but didn't look up. Elia, Sweetheart, I need you to tell me exactly what happened. Every detail. She finally raised her head, and I saw her eyes were red from crying. But there was something else there, too. Anger. Maybe even disgust. I was in my room, she said, her voice barely a whisper.

Ten year old Rebecca was found lifeless on the side of the highway. And as soon as medical professionals saw her, they knew that she had experienced severe abuse. Her toenails were missing, her entire body was covered in bruises. She had two black eyes. She was also severely malnourished. And then several days later, she lost her life.
